# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: numpy-arrays
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] Welcome to the absolute beginner’s guide to NumPy!
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] NumPy (**Num**erical **Py**thon) is an open source Python library that’s widely used in science and engineering.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] The NumPy library contains multidimensional array data structures, such as the homogeneous, N-dimensional `ndarray`, and a large library of functions that operate efficiently on these data structures.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] Learn more about NumPy at What is NumPy, and if you have comments or suggestions, please reach out!
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] This widespread convention allows access to NumPy features with a short, recognizable prefix (`np.`) while distinguishing NumPy features from others that have the same name.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] Text preceded by `>>>` or `...` is **input**, the code that you would enter in a script or at a Python prompt.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] Everything else is **output**, the results of running your code.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] Note that `>>>` and `...` are not part of the code and may cause an error if entered at a Python prompt.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] To run the code in the examples, you can copy and paste it into a Python script or REPL, or use the experimental interactive examples in the browser provided in various locations in the documentation.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] Python lists are excellent, general-purpose containers.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] They can be “heterogeneous”, meaning that they can contain elements of a variety of types, and they are quite fast when used to perform individual operations on a handful of elements.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] NumPy shines when there are large quantities of “homogeneous” (same-type) data to be processed on the CPU.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] In computer programming, an array is a structure for storing and retrieving data.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] We often talk about an array as if it were a grid in space, with each cell storing one element of the data.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] A three-dimensional array would be like a set of tables, perhaps stacked as though they were printed on separate pages.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] In NumPy, this idea is generalized to an arbitrary number of dimensions, and so the fundamental array class is called `ndarray`: it represents an “N-dimensional array”.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] Most NumPy arrays have some restrictions.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] When these conditions are met, NumPy exploits these characteristics to make the array faster, more memory efficient, and more convenient to use than less restrictive data structures.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] For the remainder of this document, we will use the word “array” to refer to an instance of `ndarray`.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] One way to initialize an array is using a Python sequence, such as a list.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] Elements of an array can be accessed in various ways.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] For instance, we can access an individual element of this array as we would access an element in the original list: using the integer index of the element within square brackets.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] As with built-in Python sequences, NumPy arrays are “0-indexed”: the first element of the array is accessed using index `0`, not `1`.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] Like the original list, the array is mutable.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] Also like the original list, Python slice notation can be used for indexing.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] One major difference is that slice indexing of a list copies the elements into a new list, but slicing an array returns a *view*: an object that refers to the data in the original array.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] The original array can be mutated using the view.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] See Copies and views for a more comprehensive explanation of when array operations return views rather than copies.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] In NumPy, a dimension of an array is sometimes referred to as an “axis”.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] This terminology may be useful to disambiguate between the dimensionality of an array and the dimensionality of the data represented by the array.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] For instance, the array `a` could represent three points, each lying within a four-dimensional space, but `a` has only two “axes”.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] Another difference between an array and a list of lists is that an element of the array can be accessed by specifying the index along each axis within a *single* set of square brackets, separated by commas.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] It is familiar practice in mathematics to refer to elements of a matrix by the row index first and the column index second.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] This happens to be true for two-dimensional arrays, but a better mental model is to think of the column index as coming *last* and the row index as *second to last*.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] This generalizes to arrays with *any* number of dimensions.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] You might hear of a 0-D (zero-dimensional) array referred to as a “scalar”, a 1-D (one-dimensional) array as a “vector”, a 2-D (two-dimensional) array as a “matrix”, or an N-D (N-dimensional, where “N” is typically an integer greater than 2) array as a “tensor”.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] The number of dimensions of an array is contained in the `ndim` attribute.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] The shape of an array is a tuple of non-negative integers that specify the number of elements along each dimension.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] The fixed, total number of elements in array is contained in the `size` attribute.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] Arrays are typically “homogeneous”, meaning that they contain elements of only one “data type”.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] The data type is recorded in the `dtype` attribute.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] Read more about array attributes here and learn about array objects here.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] The function `empty` creates an array whose initial content is random and depends on the state of the memory.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] The reason to use `empty` over `zeros` (or something similar) is speed - just make sure to fill every element afterwards!
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] And even an array that contains a range of evenly spaced intervals.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] To do this, you will specify the **first number**, **last number**, and the **step size**.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] While the default data type is floating point (`np.float64`), you can explicitly specify which data type you want using the `dtype` keyword.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] Sorting an array is simple with `np.sort()`.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] You can specify the axis, kind, and order when you call the function.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] To read more about sorting an array, see: `sort`.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] You can concatenate them with `np.concatenate()`.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] In order to remove elements from an array, it’s simple to use indexing to select the elements that you want to keep.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] To read more about concatenate, see: `concatenate`.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] `ndarray.ndim` will tell you the number of axes, or dimensions, of the array.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] `ndarray.size` will tell you the total number of elements of the array.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] This is the *product* of the elements of the array’s shape.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] `ndarray.shape` will display a tuple of integers that indicate the number of elements stored along each dimension of the array.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] If, for example, you have a 2-D array with 2 rows and 3 columns, the shape of your array is `(2, 3)`.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] Using `arr.reshape()` will return a reshaped array without changing the data.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] Just remember that when you use the reshape method, the array you want to produce needs to have the same number of elements as the original array.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] If you start with an array with 12 elements, you’ll need to make sure that your new array also has a total of 12 elements.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] You can use `reshape()` to reshape your array.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] You can specify an integer or a tuple of integers.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] If you specify an integer, the result will be an array of that length.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] The shape should be compatible with the original shape.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] `order:` `C` means to read/write the elements using C-like index order, `F` means to read/write the elements using Fortran-like index order, `A` means to read/write the elements in Fortran-like index order if a is Fortran contiguous in memory, C-like order otherwise.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] If you want to learn more about C and Fortran order, you can read more about the internal organization of NumPy arrays here.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] Essentially, C and Fortran orders have to do with how indices correspond to the order the array is stored in memory.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] In Fortran, when moving through the elements of a two-dimensional array as it is stored in memory, the **first** index is the most rapidly varying index.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] As the first index moves to the next row as it changes, the matrix is stored one column at a time.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] This is why Fortran is thought of as a **Column-major language**.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] In C on the other hand, the **last** index changes the most rapidly.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] The matrix is stored by rows, making it a **Row-major language**.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] What you do for C or Fortran depends on whether it’s more important to preserve the indexing convention or not reorder the data.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] Learn more about shape manipulation here.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] You can use `np.newaxis` and `np.expand_dims` to increase the dimensions of your existing array.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] Using `np.newaxis` will increase the dimensions of your array by one dimension when used once.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] This means that a **1D** array will become a **2D** array, a **2D** array will become a **3D** array, and so on.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] You can explicitly convert a 1D array to either a row vector or a column vector using `np.newaxis`.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] You can also expand an array by inserting a new axis at a specified position with `np.expand_dims`.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] Find more information about newaxis here and `expand_dims` at `expand_dims`.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] You can index and slice NumPy arrays in the same ways you can slice Python lists.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] You may want to take a section of your array or specific array elements to use in further analysis or additional operations.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] To do that, you’ll need to subset, slice, and/or index your arrays.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] If you want to select values from your array that fulfill certain conditions, it’s straightforward with NumPy.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] You can easily print all of the values in the array that are less than 5.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] You can also select, for example, numbers that are equal to or greater than 5, and use that condition to index an array.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] You can also make use of the logical operators **&** and **|** in order to return boolean values that specify whether or not the values in an array fulfill a certain condition.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] This can be useful with arrays that contain names or other categorical values.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] You can also use `np.nonzero()` to select elements or indices from an array.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] In this example, a tuple of arrays was returned: one for each dimension.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] The first array represents the row indices where these values are found, and the second array represents the column indices where the values are found.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] If you want to generate a list of coordinates where the elements exist, you can zip the arrays, iterate over the list of coordinates, and print them.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] If the element you’re looking for doesn’t exist in the array, then the returned array of indices will be empty.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] Learn more about indexing and slicing here and here.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] Read more about using the nonzero function at: `nonzero`.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] You can easily create a new array from a section of an existing array.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] You can create a new array from a section of your array any time by specifying where you want to slice your array.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] Here, you grabbed a section of your array from index position 3 through index position 8 but not including position 8 itself.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] You can also stack two existing arrays, both vertically and horizontally.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] You can split an array into several smaller arrays using `hsplit`.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] You can specify either the number of equally shaped arrays to return or the columns *after* which the division should occur.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] Learn more about stacking and splitting arrays here.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] You can use the `view` method to create a new array object that looks at the same data as the original array (a *shallow copy*).
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] NumPy functions, as well as operations like indexing and slicing, will return views whenever possible.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] This saves memory and is faster (no copy of the data has to be made).
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] However it’s important to be aware of this - modifying data in a view also modifies the original array!
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] Now we create an array `b1` by slicing `a` and modify the first element of `b1`.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] This will modify the corresponding element in `a` as well!
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] Using the `copy` method will make a complete copy of the array and its data (a *deep copy*).
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] Once you’ve created your arrays, you can start to work with them.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] You can add the arrays together with the plus sign.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] You can, of course, do more than just addition!
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] If you want to find the sum of the elements in an array, you’d use `sum()`.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] This works for 1D arrays, 2D arrays, and arrays in higher dimensions.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] To add the rows or the columns in a 2D array, you would specify the axis.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] There are times when you might want to carry out an operation between an array and a single number (also called *an operation between a vector and a scalar*) or between arrays of two different sizes.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] For example, your array (we’ll call it “data”) might contain information about distance in miles but you want to convert the information to kilometers.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] NumPy understands that the multiplication should happen with each cell.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] That concept is called **broadcasting**.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] Broadcasting is a mechanism that allows NumPy to perform operations on arrays of different shapes.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] The dimensions of your array must be compatible, for example, when the dimensions of both arrays are equal or when one of them is 1.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] If the dimensions are not compatible, you will get a `ValueError`.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] NumPy also performs aggregation functions.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] In addition to `min`, `max`, and `sum`, you can easily run `mean` to get the average, `prod` to get the result of multiplying the elements together, `std` to get the standard deviation, and more.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] It’s very common to want to aggregate along a row or column.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] By default, every NumPy aggregation function will return the aggregate of the entire array.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] You can specify on which axis you want the aggregation function to be computed.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] For example, you can find the minimum value within each column by specifying `axis=0`.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] The four values listed above correspond to the number of columns in your array.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] With a four-column array, you will get four values as your result.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] You can pass Python lists of lists to create a 2-D array (or “matrix”) to represent them in NumPy.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] You can aggregate all the values in a matrix and you can aggregate them across columns or rows using the `axis` parameter.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] Once you’ve created your matrices, you can add and multiply them using arithmetic operators if you have two matrices that are the same size.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] You can do these arithmetic operations on matrices of different sizes, but only if one matrix has only one column or one row.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] In this case, NumPy will use its broadcast rules for the operation.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] Be aware that when NumPy prints N-dimensional arrays, the last axis is looped over the fastest while the first axis is the slowest.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] There are often instances where we want NumPy to initialize the values of an array.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] NumPy offers functions like `ones()` and `zeros()`, and the `random.Generator` class for random number generation for that.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] Read more about creating arrays, filled with `0`’s, `1`’s, other values or uninitialized, at array creation routines.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] The use of random number generation is an important part of the configuration and evaluation of many numerical and machine learning algorithms.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] Whether you need to randomly initialize weights in an artificial neural network, split data into random sets, or randomly shuffle your dataset, being able to generate random numbers (actually, repeatable pseudo-random numbers) is essential.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] With `Generator.integers`, you can generate random integers from low (remember that this is inclusive with NumPy) to high (exclusive).
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] You can set `endpoint=True` to make the high number inclusive.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] Read more about random number generation here.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] You can find the unique elements in an array easily with `np.unique`.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] To get the indices of unique values in a NumPy array (an array of first index positions of unique values in the array), just pass the `return_index` argument in `np.unique()` as well as your array.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] You can pass the `return_counts` argument in `np.unique()` along with your array to get the frequency count of unique values in a NumPy array.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] If the axis argument isn’t passed, your 2D array will be flattened.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] If you want to get the unique rows or columns, make sure to pass the `axis` argument.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] To find the unique rows, specify `axis=0` and for columns, specify `axis=1`.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] To learn more about finding the unique elements in an array, see `unique`.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] It’s common to need to transpose your matrices.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] NumPy arrays have the property `T` that allows you to transpose a matrix.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] You may also need to switch the dimensions of a matrix.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] This can happen when, for example, you have a model that expects a certain input shape that is different from your dataset.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] This is where the `reshape` method can be useful.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] You simply need to pass in the new dimensions that you want for the matrix.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] You can also use `.transpose()` to reverse or change the axes of an array according to the values you specify.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] You can transpose your array with `arr.transpose()`.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] To learn more about transposing and reshaping arrays, see `transpose` and `reshape`.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] NumPy’s `np.flip()` function allows you to flip, or reverse, the contents of an array along an axis.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] When using `np.flip()`, specify the array you would like to reverse and the axis.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] If you don’t specify the axis, NumPy will reverse the contents along all of the axes of your input array.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] You can also reverse the contents of only one column or row.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] Read more about reversing arrays at `flip`.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] There are two popular ways to flatten an array: `.flatten()` and `.ravel()`.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] The primary difference between the two is that the new array created using `ravel()` is actually a reference to the parent array (i.e., a “view”).
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] This means that any changes to the new array will affect the parent array as well.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] Since `ravel` does not create a copy, it’s memory efficient.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] You can use `flatten` to flatten your array into a 1D array.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] When you use `flatten`, changes to your new array won’t change the parent array.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] But when you use `ravel`, the changes you make to the new array will affect the parent array.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] Read more about `flatten` at `ndarray.flatten` and `ravel` at `ravel`.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] When it comes to the data science ecosystem, Python and NumPy are built with the user in mind.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] One of the best examples of this is the built-in access to documentation.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] Every object contains the reference to a string, which is known as the **docstring**.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] In most cases, this docstring contains a quick and concise summary of the object and how to use it.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] Python has a built-in `help()` function that can help you access this information.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] This means that nearly any time you need more information, you can use `help()` to quickly find the information that you need.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] Because access to additional information is so useful, IPython uses the `?` character as a shorthand for accessing this documentation along with other relevant information.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] IPython is a command shell for interactive computing in multiple languages.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] You can find more information about IPython here.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] You can even use this notation for object methods and objects themselves.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] This also works for functions and other objects that **you** create.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] Just remember to include a docstring with your function using a string literal (`""" """` or `''' '''` around your documentation).
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] You can reach another level of information by reading the source code of the object you’re interested in.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] Using a double question mark (`??`) allows you to access the source code.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] If the object in question is compiled in a language other than Python, using `??` will return the same information as `?`.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] have the same output because they were compiled in a programming language other than Python.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] The ease of implementing mathematical formulas that work on arrays is one of the things that make NumPy so widely used in the scientific Python community.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] What makes this work so well is that `predictions` and `labels` can contain one or a thousand values.
