[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] You will, at some point, want to save your arrays to disk and load them back without having to re-run the code.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] Fortunately, there are several ways to save and load objects with NumPy.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] The **.npy** and **.npz** files store data, shape, dtype, and other information required to reconstruct the ndarray in a way that allows the array to be correctly retrieved, even when the file is on another machine with different architecture.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] If you want to store a single ndarray object, store it as a .npy file using `np.save`.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] If you want to store more than one ndarray object in a single file, save it as a .npz file using `np.savez`.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] You can also save several arrays into a single file in compressed npz format with `savez_compressed`.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] It’s easy to save and load an array with `np.save()`.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] Just make sure to specify the array you want to save and a file name.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] You can use `np.load()` to reconstruct your array.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] You can save a NumPy array as a plain text file like a **.csv** or **.txt** file with `np.savetxt`.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] The `savetxt()` and `loadtxt()` functions accept additional optional parameters such as header, footer, and delimiter.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] While text files can be easier for sharing, .npy and .npz files are smaller and faster to read.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] If you need more sophisticated handling of your text file (for example, if you need to work with lines that contain missing values), you will want to use the `genfromtxt` function.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] With `savetxt`, you can specify headers, footers, comments, and more.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] Learn more about input and output routines here.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] It’s simple to read in a CSV that contains existing information.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] The best and easiest way to do this is to use Pandas.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] It’s simple to use Pandas in order to export your array as well.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] If you are new to NumPy, you may want to create a Pandas dataframe from the values in your array and then write the data frame to a CSV file with Pandas.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] You can also save your array with the NumPy `savetxt` method.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] Or you can open the file any time with a text editor!
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] If you’re interested in learning more about Pandas, take a look at the official Pandas documentation.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] Learn how to install Pandas with the official Pandas installation information.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] If you need to generate a plot for your values, it’s very simple with Matplotlib.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] With Matplotlib, you have access to an enormous number of visualization options.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] To read more about Matplotlib and what it can do, take a look at the official documentation.
[src:numpy-arrays/absolute-beginners] For directions regarding installing Matplotlib, see the official installation section.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] In computer science, an **array** is a data structure consisting of a collection of *elements* (values or variables), of the same memory size, each identified by at least one *array index* or *key*, the collection of which may be a tuple, known as an index tuple.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] In general, an array is a mutable and linear collection of elements with the same data type.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] An array is stored such that the position (memory address) of each element can be computed from its index tuple by a mathematical formula.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] The simplest type of data structure is a linear array, also called a one-dimensional array.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] For example, an array of ten 32-bit (4-byte) integer variables, with indices 0 through 9, may be stored as ten words at memory addresses 2000, 2004, 2008, ..., 2036, (in hexadecimal: `0x7D0`, `0x7D4`, `0x7D8`, ..., `0x7F4`) so that the element with index *i* has the address 2000 + (*i* × 4).
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] The memory address of the first element of an array is called first address, foundation address, or base address.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] Because the mathematical concept of a matrix can be represented as a two-dimensional grid, two-dimensional arrays are also sometimes called "matrices".
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] In some cases the term "vector" is used in computing to refer to an array, although tuples rather than vectors are the more mathematically correct equivalent.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] Tables are often implemented in the form of arrays, especially lookup tables; the word "table" is sometimes used as a synonym of array.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] Arrays are among the oldest and most important data structures, and are used by almost every program.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] They are also used to implement many other data structures, such as lists and strings.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] They effectively exploit the addressing logic of computers.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] In most modern computers and many external storage devices, the memory is a one-dimensional array of words, whose indices are their addresses.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] Processors, especially vector processors, are often optimized for array operations.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] Arrays are useful mostly because the element indices can be computed at run time.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] Among other things, this feature allows a single iterative statement to process arbitrarily many elements of an array.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] For that reason, the elements of an array data structure are required to have the same size and should use the same data representation.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] The set of valid index tuples and the addresses of the elements (and hence the element addressing formula) are usually, but not always, fixed while the array is in use.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] The term "array" may also refer to an array data type, a kind of data type provided by most high-level programming languages that consists of a collection of values or variables that can be selected by one or more indices computed at run-time.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] Array types are often implemented by array structures; however, in some languages they may be implemented by hash tables, linked lists, search trees, or other data structures.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] The term is also used, especially in the description of algorithms, to mean associative array or "abstract array", a theoretical computer science model (an abstract data type or ADT) intended to capture the essential properties of arrays.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] The first digital computers used machine-language programming to set up and access array structures for data tables, vector and matrix computations, and for many other purposes.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] John von Neumann wrote the first array-sorting program (merge sort) in 1945, during the building of the first stored-program computer.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] Array indexing was originally done by self-modifying code, and later using index registers and indirect addressing.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] Some mainframes designed in the 1960s, such as the Burroughs B5000 and its successors, used memory segmentation to perform index-bounds checking in hardware.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] Assembly languages generally have no special support for arrays, other than what the machine itself provides.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] The earliest high-level programming languages, including FORTRAN (1957), Lisp (1958), COBOL (1960), and ALGOL 60 (1960), had support for multi-dimensional arrays, and so has C (1972).
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] In C++ (1983), class templates exist for multi-dimensional arrays whose dimension is fixed at runtime as well as for runtime-flexible arrays.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] Arrays are used to implement mathematical vectors and matrices, as well as other kinds of rectangular tables.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] Many databases, small and large, consist of (or include) one-dimensional arrays whose elements are records.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] Arrays are used to implement other data structures, such as lists, heaps, hash tables, deques, queues, stacks, strings, and VLists.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] One or more large arrays are sometimes used to emulate in-program dynamic memory allocation, particularly memory pool allocation.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] Historically, this has sometimes been the only way to allocate "dynamic memory" portably.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] Arrays can be used to determine partial or complete control flow in programs, as a compact alternative to (otherwise repetitive) multiple `IF` statements.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] In this context, they are known as control tables and are used in conjunction with a purpose-built interpreter whose control flow is altered according to values contained in the array.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] The array may contain subroutine pointers (or relative subroutine numbers that can be acted upon by SWITCH statements) that direct the path of the execution of the program.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] When data objects are stored in an array, individual objects are selected by an index that is usually a non-negative scalar integer.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] An index *maps* the array value to a stored object.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] The first element of the array is indexed by subscript of 0.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] The first element of the array is indexed by subscript of 1.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] The base index of an array can be freely chosen.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] Using zero based indexing is the design choice of many influential programming languages, including C, Java and Lisp.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] This leads to simpler implementation where the subscript refers to an offset from the starting position of an array, so the first element has an offset of zero.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] Arrays can have multiple dimensions, thus it is not uncommon to access an array using multiple indices.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] For example, a two-dimensional array `A` with three rows and four columns might provide access to the element at the 2nd row and 4th column by the expression `A[1][3]` in the case of a zero-based indexing system.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] Thus two indices are used for a two-dimensional array, three for a three-dimensional array, and *n* for an *n*-dimensional array.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] The number of indices needed to specify an element is called the dimension, dimensionality, or rank of the array.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] In standard arrays, each index is restricted to a certain range of consecutive integers (or consecutive values of some enumerated type), and the address of an element is computed by a "linear" formula on the indices.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] A one-dimensional array (or single dimension array) is a type of linear array.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] Accessing its elements involves a single subscript which can either represent a row or column index.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] As an example consider the C declaration `int a[10];` which declares a one-dimensional array named `a` of ten integers.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] Here, the array can store ten elements of type `int` .
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] This array has indices starting from zero through nine.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] For example, the expressions `a[0]` and `a[9]` are the first and last elements respectively.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] For a vector with linear addressing, the element with index *i* is located at the address *B* + *c* · *i*, where *B* is a fixed *base address* and *c* a fixed constant, sometimes called the *address increment* or *stride*.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] If the valid element indices begin at 0, the constant *B* is simply the address of the first element of the array.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] For this reason, the C programming language specifies that array indices always begin at 0; and many programmers will call that element "zeroth" rather than "first".
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] However, one can choose the index of the first element by an appropriate choice of the base address *B*.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] For example, if the array has five elements, indexed 1 through 5, and the base address *B* is replaced by *B* + 30*c*, then the indices of those same elements will be 31 to 35.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] If the numbering does not start at 0, the constant *B* may not be the address of any element.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] For a multidimensional array, the element with indices *i*,*j* would have address *B* + *c* · *i* + *d* · *j*, where the coefficients *c* and *d* are the *row* and *column address increments*, respectively.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] This means that array a has 2 rows and 3 columns, and the array is of integer type.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] Here we can store 6 elements they will be stored linearly but starting from first row linear then continuing with second row.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] This formula requires only *k* multiplications and *k* additions, for any array that can fit in memory.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] Moreover, if any coefficient is a fixed power of 2, the multiplication can be replaced by bit shifting.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] The coefficients *c**k* must be chosen so that every valid index tuple maps to the address of a distinct element.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] If the minimum legal value for every index is 0, then *B* is the address of the element whose indices are all zero.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] As in the one-dimensional case, the element indices may be changed by changing the base address *B*.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] Thus, if a two-dimensional array has rows and columns indexed from 1 to 10 and 1 to 20, respectively, then replacing *B* by *B* + *c*1 − 3*c*2 will cause them to be renumbered from 0 through 9 and 4 through 23, respectively.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] Taking advantage of this feature, some languages (like FORTRAN 77) specify that array indices begin at 1, as in mathematical tradition while other languages (like Fortran 90, Pascal and Algol) let the user choose the minimum value for each index.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] The addressing formula is completely defined by the dimension *d*, the base address *B*, and the increments *c*1, *c*2, ..., *c**k*.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] It is often useful to pack these parameters into a record called the array's descriptor, stride vector, or dope vector.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] The size of each element, and the minimum and maximum values allowed for each index may also be included in the dope vector.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] The dope vector is a complete handle for the array, and is a convenient way to pass arrays as arguments to procedures.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] Many useful array slicing operations (such as selecting a sub-array, swapping indices, or reversing the direction of the indices) can be performed very efficiently by manipulating the dope vector.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] Often the coefficients are chosen so that the elements occupy a contiguous area of memory.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] Even if arrays are always created with contiguous elements, some array slicing operations may create non-contiguous sub-arrays from them.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] There are two systematic compact layouts for a two-dimensional array.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] For arrays with three or more indices, "row major order" puts in consecutive positions any two elements whose index tuples differ only by one in the *last* index.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] "Column major order" is analogous with respect to the *first* index.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] In systems which use processor cache or virtual memory, scanning an array is much faster if successive elements are stored in consecutive positions in memory, rather than sparsely scattered.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] This is known as spatial locality, which is a type of locality of reference.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] Many algorithms that use multidimensional arrays will scan them in a predictable order.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] A programmer (or a sophisticated compiler) may use this information to choose between row- or column-major layout for each array.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] For example, when computing the product *A*·*B* of two matrices, it would be best to have *A* stored in row-major order, and *B* in column-major order.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] Static arrays have a size that is fixed when they are created and consequently do not allow elements to be inserted or removed.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] However, by allocating a new array and copying the contents of the old array to it, it is possible to effectively implement a *dynamic* version of an array; see dynamic array.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] If this operation is done infrequently, insertions at the end of the array require only amortized constant time.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] Some array data structures do not reallocate storage, but do store a count of the number of elements of the array in use, called the count or size.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] This effectively makes the array a dynamic array with a fixed maximum size or capacity; Pascal strings are examples of this.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] More complicated (non-linear) formulas are occasionally used.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] For a compact two-dimensional triangular array, for instance, the addressing formula is a polynomial of degree 2.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] Both *store* and *select* take (deterministic worst case) constant time.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] Arrays take linear (O(*n*)) space in the number of elements *n* that they hold.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] In an array with element size *k* and on a machine with a cache line size of B bytes, iterating through an array of *n* elements requires the minimum of ceiling(*nk*/B) cache misses, because its elements occupy contiguous memory locations.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] This is roughly a factor of B/*k* better than the number of cache misses needed to access *n* elements at random memory locations.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] Libraries provide low-level optimized facilities for copying ranges of memory (such as memcpy) which can be used to move contiguous blocks of array elements significantly faster than can be achieved through individual element access.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] The speedup of such optimized routines varies by array element size, architecture, and implementation.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] Memory-wise, arrays are compact data structures with no per-element overhead.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] There may be a per-array overhead (e.g., to store index bounds) but this is language-dependent.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] It can also happen that elements stored in an array require *less* memory than the same elements stored in individual variables, because several array elements can be stored in a single word; such arrays are often called *packed* arrays.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] An extreme (but commonly used) case is the bit array, where every bit represents a single element.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] A single octet can thus hold up to 256 different combinations of up to 8 different conditions, in the most compact form.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] Array accesses with statically predictable access patterns are a major source of data parallelism.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] Dynamic arrays or growable arrays are similar to arrays but add the ability to insert and delete elements; adding and deleting at the end is particularly efficient.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] However, they reserve linear (Θ(*n*)) additional storage, whereas arrays do not reserve additional storage.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] Associative arrays provide a mechanism for array-like functionality without huge storage overheads when the index values are sparse.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] For example, an array that contains values only at indexes 1 and 2 billion may benefit from using such a structure.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] Specialized associative arrays with integer keys include Patricia tries, Judy arrays, and van Emde Boas trees.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] Balanced trees require O(log *n*) time for indexed access, but also permit inserting or deleting elements in O(log *n*) time, whereas growable arrays require linear (Θ(*n*)) time to insert or delete elements at an arbitrary position.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] Linked lists allow constant time removal and insertion in the middle but take linear time for indexed access.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] Their memory use is typically worse than arrays, but is still linear.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] An Iliffe vector is an alternative to a multidimensional array structure.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] It uses a one-dimensional array of references to arrays of one dimension less.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] For two dimensions, in particular, this alternative structure would be a vector of pointers to vectors, one for each row(pointer on c or c++).
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] Thus an element in row *i* and column *j* of an array *A* would be accessed by double indexing (*A*[*i*][*j*] in typical notation).
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] This alternative structure allows jagged arrays, where each row may have a different size—or, in general, where the valid range of each index depends on the values of all preceding indices.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] It also saves one multiplication (by the column address increment) replacing it by a bit shift (to index the vector of row pointers) and one extra memory access (fetching the row address), which may be worthwhile in some architectures.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] The *dimension* of an array is the number of indices needed to select an element.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] Thus, if the array is seen as a function on a set of possible index combinations, it is the dimension of the space of which its domain is a discrete subset.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] Thus a one-dimensional array is a list of data, a two-dimensional array is a rectangle of data, a three-dimensional array a block of data, etc.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] This should not be confused with the dimension of the set of all matrices with a given domain, that is, the number of elements in the array.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] For example, an array with 5 rows and 4 columns is two-dimensional, but such matrices form a 20-dimensional space.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-data-structure] Similarly, a three-dimensional vector can be represented by a one-dimensional array of size three.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-programming] In computer science, **array programming** refers to solutions that allow the application of operations to an entire set of values at once.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-programming] Such solutions are commonly used in scientific and engineering settings.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-programming] Modern programming languages that support array programming (also known as vector or multidimensional languages) have been engineered specifically to generalize operations on scalars to apply transparently to vectors, matrices, and higher-dimensional arrays.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-programming] These include APL, J, Fortran, MATLAB, Analytica, Octave, PL/I, R, Cilk Plus, Julia, Perl Data Language (PDL) and Raku.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-programming] In these languages, an operation that operates on entire arrays can be called a *vectorized* operation, regardless of whether it is executed on a vector processor, which implements vector instructions.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-programming] Array programming primitives concisely express broad ideas about data manipulation.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-programming] The level of concision can be dramatic in certain cases: it is not uncommon to find array programming language one-liners that require several pages of object-oriented code.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-programming] The fundamental idea behind array programming is that operations apply at once to an entire set of values.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-programming] This makes it a high-level programming model as it allows the programmer to think and operate on whole aggregates of data, without having to resort to explicit loops of individual scalar operations.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-programming] The basis behind array programming and thinking is to find and exploit the properties of data where individual elements are similar or adjacent.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-programming] Unlike object orientation which implicitly breaks down data to its constituent parts (or scalar quantities), array orientation looks to group data and apply a uniform handling.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-programming] Function rank is an important concept to array programming languages in general, by analogy to tensor rank in mathematics: functions that operate on data may be classified by the number of dimensions they act on.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-programming] Ordinary multiplication, for example, is a scalar ranked function because it operates on zero-dimensional data (individual numbers).
[src:numpy-arrays/array-programming] The cross product operation is an example of a vector rank function because it operates on vectors, not scalars.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-programming] Matrix multiplication is an example of a 2-rank function, because it operates on 2-dimensional objects (matrices).
[src:numpy-arrays/array-programming] Collapse operators reduce the dimensionality of an input data array by one or more dimensions.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-programming] For example, summing over elements collapses the input array by 1 dimension.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-programming] Array programming is very well suited to implicit parallelization; a topic of much research nowadays.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-programming] Further, Intel and compatible CPUs developed and produced after 1997 contained various instruction set extensions, starting from MMX and continuing through SSSE3 and 3DNow!, which include rudimentary SIMD array capabilities.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-programming] This has continued into the 2020s with instruction sets such as AVX-512, making modern CPUs sophisticated vector processors.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-programming] Array processing is distinct from parallel processing in that one physical processor performs operations on a group of items simultaneously while parallel processing aims to split a larger problem into smaller ones (MIMD) to be solved piecemeal by numerous processors.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-programming] Processors with multiple cores and GPUs with thousands of general computing cores are common as of 2023.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-programming] The canonical examples of array programming languages are Fortran, APL, and J.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-programming] Others include: A+, Analytica, Chapel, IDL, Julia, K, Klong, Q, MATLAB, GNU Octave, Scilab, FreeMat, Perl Data Language (PDL), R, Raku, S-Lang, SAC, Nial, ZPL, Futhark, and TI-BASIC.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-programming] In scalar languages such as C and Pascal, operations apply only to single values, so *a*+*b* expresses the addition of two numbers.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-programming] In such languages, adding one array to another requires indexing and looping, the coding of which is tedious.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-programming] Some C compilers like GCC at some optimization levels detect and vectorize sections of code that its heuristics determine would benefit from it.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-programming] Another approach is given by the OpenMP API, which allows one to parallelize applicable sections of code by taking advantage of multiple CPU cores.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-programming] In array languages, operations are generalized to apply to both scalars and arrays.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-programming] Thus, *a*+*b* expresses the sum of two scalars if *a* and *b* are scalars, or the sum of two arrays if they are arrays.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-programming] An array language simplifies programming but possibly at a cost known as the *abstraction penalty*.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-programming] Because the additions are performed in isolation from the rest of the coding, they may not produce the optimally most efficient code.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-programming] The previous C code would become the following in the Ada language, which supports array-programming syntax.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-programming] APL uses single character Unicode symbols with no syntactic sugar.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-programming] This operation works on arrays of any rank (including rank 0), and on a scalar and an array.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-programming] Analytica provides the same economy of expression as Ada.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-programming] Dartmouth BASIC had MAT statements for matrix and array manipulation in its third edition (1966).
[src:numpy-arrays/array-programming] Stata's matrix programming language Mata supports array programming.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-programming] Below, we illustrate addition, multiplication, addition of a matrix and a scalar, element by element multiplication, subscripting, and one of Mata's many inverse matrix functions.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-programming] The implementation in MATLAB allows the same economy allowed by using the Fortran language.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-programming] Both MATLAB and GNU Octave natively support linear algebra operations such as matrix multiplication, matrix inversion, and the numerical solution of system of linear equations, even using the Moore–Penrose pseudoinverse.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-programming] The Nial example of the inner product of two arrays can be implemented using the native matrix multiplication operator.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-programming] If `a` is a row vector of size [1 n] and `b` is a corresponding column vector of size [n 1].
[src:numpy-arrays/array-programming] The rasdaman query language is a database-oriented array-programming language.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-programming] The R language supports array paradigm by default.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-programming] Raku supports the array paradigm via its Metaoperators.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-programming] The following example demonstrates the addition of arrays @a and @b using the Hyper-operator in conjunction with the plus operator.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-programming] The matrix left-division operator concisely expresses some semantic properties of matrices.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-programming] As in the scalar equivalent, if the (determinant of the) coefficient (matrix) `A` is not null then it is possible to solve the (vectorial) equation `A * x = b` by left-multiplying both sides by the inverse of `A`: `A−1` (in both MATLAB and GNU Octave languages: `A^-1`).
[src:numpy-arrays/array-programming] where `==` is the equivalence relational operator.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-programming] The previous statements are also valid MATLAB expressions if the third one is executed before the others (numerical comparisons may be false because of round-off errors).
[src:numpy-arrays/array-programming] However, these solutions are neither the most concise ones (e.g. still remains the need to notationally differentiate overdetermined systems) nor the most computationally efficient.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-programming] The latter point is easy to understand when considering again the scalar equivalent `a * x = b`, for which the solution `x = a^-1 * b` would require two operations instead of the more efficient `x = b / a`.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-programming] This is not only an example of terse array programming from the coding point of view but also from the computational efficiency perspective, which in several array programming languages benefits from quite efficient linear algebra libraries such as ATLAS or LAPACK.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-programming] The use of specialized and efficient libraries to provide more terse abstractions is also common in other programming languages.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-programming] In C++ several linear algebra libraries exploit the language's ability to overload operators.
[src:numpy-arrays/array-programming] In some cases a very terse abstraction in those languages is explicitly influenced by the array programming paradigm, as the NumPy extension library to Python, Armadillo and Blitz++ libraries do.
[src:numpy-arrays/basics-broadcasting] The term broadcasting describes how NumPy treats arrays with different shapes during arithmetic operations.
[src:numpy-arrays/basics-broadcasting] Subject to certain constraints, the smaller array is “broadcast” across the larger array so that they have compatible shapes.
[src:numpy-arrays/basics-broadcasting] Broadcasting provides a means of vectorizing array operations so that looping occurs in C instead of Python.
[src:numpy-arrays/basics-broadcasting] It does this without making needless copies of data and usually leads to efficient algorithm implementations.
[src:numpy-arrays/basics-broadcasting] There are, however, cases where broadcasting is a bad idea because it leads to inefficient use of memory that slows computation.
[src:numpy-arrays/basics-broadcasting] NumPy operations are usually done on pairs of arrays on an element-by-element basis.
[src:numpy-arrays/basics-broadcasting] NumPy’s broadcasting rule relaxes this constraint when the arrays’ shapes meet certain constraints.
[src:numpy-arrays/basics-broadcasting] The result is equivalent to the previous example where `b` was an array.
[src:numpy-arrays/basics-broadcasting] We can think of the scalar `b` being *stretched* during the arithmetic operation into an array with the same shape as `a`.
[src:numpy-arrays/basics-broadcasting] The new elements in `b`, as shown in Figure 1, are simply copies of the original scalar.
[src:numpy-arrays/basics-broadcasting] The stretching analogy is only conceptual.
[src:numpy-arrays/basics-broadcasting] NumPy is smart enough to use the original scalar value without actually making copies so that broadcasting operations are as memory and computationally efficient as possible.
[src:numpy-arrays/basics-broadcasting] The code in the second example is more efficient than that in the first because broadcasting moves less memory around during the multiplication (`b` is a scalar rather than an array).
[src:numpy-arrays/basics-broadcasting] When operating on two arrays, NumPy compares their shapes element-wise.
[src:numpy-arrays/basics-broadcasting] It starts with the trailing (i.e. rightmost) dimension and works its way left.
[src:numpy-arrays/basics-broadcasting] If these conditions are not met, a `ValueError: operands could not be broadcast together` exception is thrown, indicating that the arrays have incompatible shapes.
[src:numpy-arrays/basics-broadcasting] Input arrays do not need to have the same *number* of dimensions.
[src:numpy-arrays/basics-broadcasting] The resulting array will have the same number of dimensions as the input array with the greatest number of dimensions, where the *size* of each dimension is the largest size of the corresponding dimension among the input arrays.
[src:numpy-arrays/basics-broadcasting] Note that missing dimensions are assumed to have size one.
[src:numpy-arrays/basics-broadcasting] For example, if you have a `256x256x3` array of RGB values, and you want to scale each color in the image by a different value, you can multiply the image by a one-dimensional array with 3 values.
[src:numpy-arrays/basics-broadcasting] When either of the dimensions compared is one, the other is used.
[src:numpy-arrays/basics-broadcasting] In other words, dimensions with size 1 are stretched or “copied” to match the other.
[src:numpy-arrays/basics-broadcasting] A set of arrays is called “broadcastable” to the same shape if the above rules produce a valid result.
[src:numpy-arrays/basics-broadcasting] As shown in Figure 2, `b` is added to each row of `a`.
[src:numpy-arrays/basics-broadcasting] In Figure 3, an exception is raised because of the incompatible shapes.
[src:numpy-arrays/basics-broadcasting] Broadcasting provides a convenient way of taking the outer product (or any other outer operation) of two arrays.
[src:numpy-arrays/basics-broadcasting] Here the `newaxis` index operator inserts a new axis into `a`, making it a two-dimensional `4x1` array.
[src:numpy-arrays/basics-broadcasting] Combining the `4x1` array with `b`, which has shape `(3,)`, yields a `4x3` array.
[src:numpy-arrays/basics-broadcasting] Broadcasting comes up quite often in real world problems.
[src:numpy-arrays/basics-broadcasting] A typical example occurs in the vector quantization (VQ) algorithm used in information theory, classification, and other related areas.
[src:numpy-arrays/basics-broadcasting] The basic operation in VQ finds the closest point in a set of points, called `codes` in VQ jargon, to a given point, called the `observation`.
[src:numpy-arrays/basics-broadcasting] In the very simple, two-dimensional case shown below, the values in `observation` describe the weight and height of an athlete to be classified.
[src:numpy-arrays/basics-broadcasting] The `codes` represent different classes of athletes. [1] Finding the closest point requires calculating the distance between observation and each of the codes.
[src:numpy-arrays/basics-broadcasting] The shortest distance provides the best match.
[src:numpy-arrays/basics-broadcasting] In this example, `codes[0]` is the closest class indicating that the athlete is likely a basketball player.
[src:numpy-arrays/basics-broadcasting] Typically, a large number of `observations`, perhaps read from a database, are compared to a set of `codes`.
[src:numpy-arrays/basics-broadcasting] The three-dimensional array, `diff`, is a consequence of broadcasting, not a necessity for the calculation.
[src:numpy-arrays/basics-broadcasting] Large data sets will generate a large intermediate array that is computationally inefficient.
[src:numpy-arrays/basics-broadcasting] Instead, if each observation is calculated individually using a Python loop around the code in the two-dimensional example above, a much smaller array is used.
[src:numpy-arrays/basics-broadcasting] Broadcasting is a powerful tool for writing short and usually intuitive code that does its computations very efficiently in C.
[src:numpy-arrays/basics-broadcasting] However, there are cases when broadcasting uses unnecessarily large amounts of memory for a particular algorithm.
[src:numpy-arrays/basics-broadcasting] In these cases, it is better to write the algorithm’s outer loop in Python.
[src:numpy-arrays/basics-broadcasting] This may also produce more readable code, as algorithms that use broadcasting tend to become more difficult to interpret as the number of dimensions in the broadcast increases.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] In mathematics, a **matrix** (pl.: **matrices**) is a rectangular array of numbers or other mathematical objects with elements or entries arranged in rows and columns, usually satisfying certain properties of addition and multiplication.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] For example, ${\begin{bmatrix}1&9&-13\\20&5&-6\end{bmatrix}}$ denotes a matrix with two rows and three columns.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] This is often referred to as a "two-by-three matrix", a 2 × 3 matrix, or a matrix of dimension 2 × 3.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] In linear algebra, matrices are used as linear maps.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] In geometry, matrices are used for geometric transformations (for example rotations) and coordinate changes.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] In numerical analysis, many computational problems are solved by reducing them to a matrix computation, and this often involves computing with matrices of huge dimensions.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] Matrices are used in most areas of mathematics and scientific fields, either directly, or through their use in geometry and numerical analysis.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] A matrix is a rectangular array of numbers (or other mathematical objects), called the "entries" of the matrix.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] Matrices are subject to standard operations such as addition and multiplication.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] Most commonly, a matrix over a field F is a rectangular array of elements of ⁠ F ⁠.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] A **real matrix** and a **complex matrix** are matrices whose entries are respectively real numbers or complex numbers.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] More general types of entries are discussed below.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] The numbers (or other objects) in the matrix are called its *entries* or its *elements*.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] The horizontal and vertical lines of entries in a matrix are respectively called *rows* and *columns*.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] The size of a matrix is defined by the number of rows and columns it contains.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] There is no limit to the number of rows and columns that a matrix (in the usual sense) can have as long as they are positive integers.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] A matrix with m rows and n columns is called an m × n matrix, or m-by-n matrix, where m and n are called its **dimensions**.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] For example, the matrix ${\mathbf {A} }$ above is a 3 × 2 matrix.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] Matrices with a single row are called *row matrices* or *row vectors*, and those with a single column are called *column matrices* or *column vectors*.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] A matrix with the same number of rows and columns is called a *square matrix*.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] A matrix with an infinite number of rows or columns (or both) is called an *infinite matrix*.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] In some contexts, such as computer algebra programs, it is useful to consider a matrix with no rows or no columns, called an *empty matrix*.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] The specifics of symbolic matrix notation vary widely, with some prevailing trends.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] Matrices are usually symbolized using upper-case letters (such as ${\mathbf {A} }$ in the examples above), while the corresponding lower-case letters, with two subscript indices (e.g., ⁠ $a_{11}$ ⁠, or ⁠ $a_{1,1}$ ⁠), represent the entries.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] In addition to using upper-case letters to symbolize matrices, many authors use a special typographical style, commonly boldface roman (non-italic), to further distinguish matrices from other mathematical objects.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] An alternative notation involves the use of a double-underline with the variable name, with or without boldface style, as in ⁠ ${\underline {\underline {A}}}$ ⁠.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] The entry in the *i*th row and *j*th column of a matrix **A** is sometimes referred to as the ${i,j}$ or $(i,j)$ entry of the matrix, and commonly denoted by $a_{i,j}$ or ⁠ $a_{ij}$ ⁠.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] Alternative notations for that entry are ${\mathbf {A} [i,j]}$ and ⁠ $\mathbf {A} _{i,j}$ ⁠.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] Sometimes, the entries of a matrix can be defined by a formula such as ⁠ $a_{i,j}=f(i,j)$ ⁠.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] For example, the matrix above is defined as ${\mathbf {A} }=[i-j]$ or ⁠ $\mathbf {A} =((i-j))$ ⁠.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] If matrix size is m × n, the above-mentioned formula $f(i,j)$ is valid for any $i=1,\dots ,m$ and any ⁠ $j=1,\dots ,n$ ⁠.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] This can be specified separately or indicated using m × n as a subscript.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] Some programming languages utilize doubly subscripted arrays (or arrays of arrays) to represent an {m-by-n matrix.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] Some programming languages start the numbering of array indexes at zero, in which case the entries of an m × n matrix are indexed by $0\leq i\leq m-1$ and ⁠ $0\leq j\leq n-1$ ⁠.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] This article follows the more common convention in mathematical writing where enumeration starts from 1.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] The set of all m-by-n real matrices is often denoted ⁠ ${\mathcal {M}}(m,n)$ ⁠, or ⁠ ${\mathcal {M}}_{m\times n}(\mathbb {R} )$ ⁠.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] The set of all m × n matrices over another field, or over a ring *R*, is similarly denoted ⁠ ${\mathcal {M}}(m,n,R)$ ⁠, or ⁠ ${\mathcal {M}}_{m\times n}(R)$ ⁠.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] If *m* = *n*, such as in the case of square matrices, one does not repeat the dimension: ⁠ ${\mathcal {M}}(n,R)$ ⁠, or ⁠ ${\mathcal {M}}_{n}(R)$ ⁠.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] Often, ⁠ M ⁠, or ⁠ $\operatorname {Mat}$ ⁠, is used in place of ⁠ ${\mathcal {M}}$ ⁠.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] Several basic operations can be applied to matrices.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] Some, such as *transposition* and *submatrix* do not depend on the nature of the entries.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] Others, such as *matrix addition*, *scalar multiplication*, *matrix multiplication*, and *row operations* involve operations on matrix entries and therefore require that matrix entries are numbers or belong to a field or a ring.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] In this section, it is supposed that matrix entries belong to a fixed ring, which is typically a field of numbers.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] Matrix addition and subtraction require matrices of a consistent size, and are calculated entrywise.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] Familiar properties of numbers extend to these operations on matrices: for example, addition is commutative, that is, the matrix sum does not depend on the order of the summands: **A** + **B** = **B** + **A**.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] The transpose is compatible with addition and scalar multiplication, as expressed by (*c***A**)T = *c*(**A**T) and (**A** + **B**)T = **A**T + **B**T.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] Matrix multiplication satisfies the rules (**AB**)**C** = **A**(**BC**) (associativity), and (**A** + **B**)**C** = **AC** + **BC** as well as **C**(**A** + **B**) = **CA** + **CB** (left and right distributivity), whenever the size of the matrices is such that the various products are defined.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] The product **AB** may be defined without **BA** being defined, namely if **A** and **B** are m × n and n × k matrices, respectively, and *m* ≠ *k*.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] In other words, matrix multiplication is not commutative, in marked contrast to (rational, real, or complex) numbers, whose product is independent of the order of the factors.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] Besides the ordinary matrix multiplication just described, other less frequently used operations on matrices that can be considered forms of multiplication also exist, such as the Hadamard product and the Kronecker product.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] They arise in solving matrix equations such as the Sylvester equation.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] These operations are used in several ways, including solving linear equations and finding matrix inverses with Gauss elimination and Gauss–Jordan elimination, respectively.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] A **submatrix** of a matrix is a matrix obtained by deleting any collection of rows or columns or both.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] The minors and cofactors of a matrix are found by computing the determinant of certain submatrices.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] A **principal submatrix** is a square submatrix obtained by removing certain rows and columns.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] The definition varies from author to author.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] According to some authors, a principal submatrix is a submatrix in which the set of row indices that remain is the same as the set of column indices that remain.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] Other authors define a principal submatrix as one in which the first k rows and columns, for some number k, are the ones that remain; this type of submatrix has also been called a **leading principal submatrix**.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] Matrices can be used to compactly write and work with multiple linear equations, that is, systems of linear equations.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] Using matrices, this can be solved more compactly than would be possible by writing out all the equations separately.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] If *n* = *m* and the equations are independent, then this can be done by writing $\mathbf {x} =\mathbf {A} ^{-1}\mathbf {b}$ where **A**−1 is the inverse matrix of **A**.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] If **A** has no inverse, solutions—if any—can be found using its generalized inverse.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] Matrices and matrix multiplication reveal their essential features when related to *linear transformations*, also known as *linear maps*.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] The matrix **A** is said to represent the linear map f, and **A** is called the *transformation matrix* of f.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] For example, the 2 × 2 matrix $\mathbf {A} ={\begin{bmatrix}a&c\\b&d\end{bmatrix}}$ can be viewed as the transform of the unit square into a parallelogram with vertices at (0, 0), (*a*, *b*), (*a* + *c*, *b* + *d*), and (*c*, *d*).
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] These vectors define the vertices of the unit square.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] The following table shows several 2 × 2 real matrices with the associated linear maps of ⁠ $\mathbb {R} ^{2}$ ⁠.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] The blue original is mapped to the green grid and shapes.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] The origin (0, 0) is marked with a black point.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] The last equality follows from the above-mentioned associativity of matrix multiplication.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] The rank of a matrix **A** is the maximum number of linearly independent row vectors of the matrix, which is the same as the maximum number of linearly independent column vectors.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] Equivalently it is the dimension of the image of the linear map represented by **A**.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] The rank–nullity theorem states that the dimension of the kernel of a matrix plus the rank equals the number of columns of the matrix.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] A square matrix is a matrix with the same number of rows and columns.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] An n-by-n matrix is known as a square matrix of order n.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] Any two square matrices of the same order can be added and multiplied.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] The entries aii form the main diagonal of a square matrix.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] They lie on the imaginary line running from the top left corner to the bottom right corner of the matrix.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] Square matrices of a given dimension form a noncommutative ring, which is one of the most common examples of a noncommutative ring.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] If all entries of **A** below the main diagonal are zero, **A** is called an *upper triangular matrix*.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] Similarly, if all entries of **A** above the main diagonal are zero, **A** is called a *lower triangular matrix*.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] If all entries outside the main diagonal are zero, **A** is called a diagonal matrix.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] It is called an identity matrix because multiplication with it leaves a matrix unchanged: ${\mathbf {AI}}_{n}={\mathbf {I}}_{m}{\mathbf {A}}={\mathbf {A}}$ for any m-by-n matrix **A**.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] A scalar multiple of an identity matrix is called a *scalar* matrix.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] A square matrix **A** that is equal to its transpose, that is, **A** = **A**T, is a symmetric matrix.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] If instead, **A** is equal to the negative of its transpose, that is, **A** = −**A**T, then **A** is a skew-symmetric matrix.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] In complex matrices, symmetry is often replaced by the concept of Hermitian matrices, which satisfies **A**∗ = **A**, where the star or asterisk denotes the conjugate transpose of the matrix, that is, the transpose of the complex conjugate of **A**.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] By the spectral theorem, real symmetric matrices and complex Hermitian matrices have an eigenbasis; that is, every vector is expressible as a linear combination of eigenvectors.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] In both cases, all eigenvalues are real.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] This theorem can be generalized to infinite-dimensional situations related to matrices with infinitely many rows and columns.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] A square matrix **A** is called *invertible* or *non-singular* if there exists a matrix **B** such that ${\mathbf {AB}}={\mathbf {BA}}={\mathbf {I}}_{n},$ where **I***n* is the n × n identity matrix with 1 for each entry on the main diagonal and 0 elsewhere.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] If **B** exists, it is unique and is called the *inverse matrix* of **A**, denoted **A**−1.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] There are many algorithms for testing whether a square matrix is invertible, and, if it is, computing its inverse.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] One of the oldest, which is still in common use is Gaussian elimination.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] A symmetric real matrix **A** is called *positive-definite* if the associated quadratic form $f({\mathbf {x}})={\mathbf {x}}^{\rm {T}}{\mathbf {Ax}}$ has a positive value for every nonzero vector **x** in ⁠ $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ ⁠.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] If *f*(**x**) yields only negative values then **A** is *negative-definite*; if f does produce both negative and positive values then **A** is *indefinite*.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] A symmetric matrix is positive-definite if and only if all its eigenvalues are positive, that is, the matrix is positive-semidefinite and it is invertible.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] The table at the right shows two possibilities for 2-by-2 matrices.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] The eigenvalues of a diagonal matrix are simply the entries along the diagonal, and so in these examples, the eigenvalues can be read directly from the matrices themselves.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] The first matrix has two eigenvalues that are both positive, while the second has one that is positive and another that is negative.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] In the case of complex matrices, the same terminology and results apply, with *symmetric matrix*, *quadratic form*, *bilinear form*, and *transpose* **x**T replaced respectively by Hermitian matrix, Hermitian form, sesquilinear form, and conjugate transpose **x**H.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] An *orthogonal matrix* is a square matrix with real entries whose columns and rows are orthogonal unit vectors (that is, orthonormal vectors).
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] Equivalently, a matrix **A** is orthogonal if its transpose is equal to its inverse: $\mathbf {A} ^{\mathrm {T} }=\mathbf {A} ^{-1},\,$ which entails $\mathbf {A} ^{\mathrm {T} }\mathbf {A} =\mathbf {A} \mathbf {A} ^{\mathrm {T} }=\mathbf {I} _{n},$ where **I***n* is the identity matrix of size n.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] The determinant of any orthogonal matrix is either +1 or −1.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] A *special orthogonal matrix* is an orthogonal matrix with determinant +1.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] The identity matrices have determinant 1 and are pure rotations by an angle zero.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] The complex analog of an orthogonal matrix is a unitary matrix.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] The trace, tr(**A**) of a square matrix **A** is the sum of its diagonal entries.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] The *determinant* of a square matrix **A** (denoted det(**A**) or |**A**|) is a number encoding certain properties of the matrix.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] A matrix is invertible if and only if its determinant is nonzero.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] Its absolute value equals the area (in ⁠ $\mathbb {R} ^{2}$ ⁠) or volume (in ⁠ $\mathbb {R} ^{3}$ ⁠) of the image of the unit square (or cube), while its sign corresponds to the orientation of the corresponding linear map: the determinant is positive if and only if the orientation is preserved.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] The determinant of 2 × 2 matrices is given by $\det {\begin{bmatrix}a&b\\c&d\end{bmatrix}}=ad-bc.$ The determinant of 3 × 3 matrices involves six terms (rule of Sarrus).
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] The more lengthy Leibniz formula generalizes these two formulae to all dimensions.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] Interchanging two rows or two columns affects the determinant by multiplying it by −1.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] Using these operations, any matrix can be transformed to a lower (or upper) triangular matrix, and for such matrices, the determinant equals the product of the entries on the main diagonal; this provides a method to calculate the determinant of any matrix.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] Finally, the Laplace expansion expresses the determinant in terms of minors, that is, determinants of smaller matrices.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] This expansion can be used for a recursive definition of determinants (taking as starting case the determinant of a 1 × 1 matrix, which is its unique entry, or even the determinant of a 0 × 0 matrix, which is 1), that can be seen to be equivalent to the Leibniz formula.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] Determinants can be used to solve linear systems using Cramer's rule, where the division of the determinants of two related square matrices equates to the value of each of the system's variables.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] A number ${\textstyle \lambda }$ and a nonzero vector **v** satisfying $\mathbf {A} \mathbf {v} =\lambda \mathbf {v}$ are called an *eigenvalue* and an *eigenvector* of **A**, respectively.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] Therefore the polynomial equation *p***A**(*λ*) = 0 has at most n different solutions, that is, eigenvalues of the matrix.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] They may be complex even if the entries of **A** are real.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] According to the Cayley–Hamilton theorem, *p***A**(**A**) = **0**, that is, the result of substituting the matrix itself into its characteristic polynomial yields the zero matrix.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] Matrix calculations can be often performed with different techniques.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] Many problems can be solved by both direct algorithms and iterative approaches.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] For example, the eigenvectors of a square matrix can be obtained by finding a sequence of vectors **x***n* converging to an eigenvector when n tends to infinity.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] To choose the most appropriate algorithm for each specific problem, it is important to determine both the effectiveness and precision of all the available algorithms.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] The domain studying these matters is called numerical linear algebra.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] As with other numerical situations, two main aspects are the complexity of algorithms and their numerical stability.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] Determining the complexity of an algorithm means finding upper bounds or estimates of how many elementary operations such as additions and multiplications of scalars are necessary to perform some algorithm, for example, multiplication of matrices.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] Calculating the matrix product of two n-by-n matrices using the definition given above needs *n*3 multiplications, since for any of the *n*2 entries of the product, n multiplications are necessary.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] The Strassen algorithm outperforms this "naive" algorithm; it needs only *n*2.807 multiplications.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] Theoretically faster but impractical matrix multiplication algorithms have been developed, as have speedups to this problem using parallel algorithms or distributed computation systems such as MapReduce.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] In many practical situations, additional information about the matrices involved is known.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] An important case concerns sparse matrices, that is, matrices whose entries are mostly zero.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] There are specifically adapted algorithms for, say, solving linear systems **Ax** = **b** for sparse matrices **A**, such as the conjugate gradient method.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] An algorithm is, roughly speaking, numerically stable if little deviations in the input values do not lead to big deviations in the result.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] For example, one can calculate the inverse of a matrix by computing its adjugate matrix: ${\mathbf {A}}^{-1}=\operatorname {adj} ({\mathbf {A}})/\det({\mathbf {A}}).$ However, this may lead to significant rounding errors if the determinant of the matrix is very small.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] The norm of a matrix can be used to capture the conditioning of linear algebraic problems, such as computing a matrix's inverse.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] There are several methods to render matrices into a more easily accessible form.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] They are generally referred to as *matrix decomposition* or *matrix factorization* techniques.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] These techniques are of interest because they can make computations easier.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] The LU decomposition factors matrices as a product of lower (**L**) and an upper triangular matrices (**U**).
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] Once this decomposition is calculated, linear systems can be solved more efficiently by a simple technique called forward and back substitution.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] Likewise, inverses of triangular matrices are algorithmically easier to calculate.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] The *Gaussian elimination* is a similar algorithm; it transforms any matrix to row echelon form.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] Both methods proceed by multiplying the matrix by suitable elementary matrices, which correspond to permuting rows or columns and adding multiples of one row to another row.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] Singular value decomposition (SVD) expresses any matrix **A** as a product **UDV**∗, where **U** and **V** are unitary matrices and **D** is a diagonal matrix.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] The eigendecomposition or *diagonalization* expresses **A** as a product **VDV**−1, where **D** is a diagonal matrix and **V** is a suitable invertible matrix.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] If **A** can be written in this form, it is called diagonalizable.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] This can be used to compute the matrix exponential *e***A**, a need frequently arising in solving linear differential equations, matrix logarithms and square roots of matrices.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] To avoid numerically ill-conditioned situations, further algorithms such as the Schur decomposition can be employed.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] Matrices can be generalized in different ways.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] Abstract algebra uses matrices with entries in more general fields or even rings, while linear algebra codifies properties of matrices in the notion of linear maps.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] It is possible to consider matrices with infinitely many columns and rows.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] Another extension is tensors, which can be seen as higher-dimensional arrays of numbers, as opposed to vectors, which can often be realized as sequences of numbers, while matrices are rectangular or two-dimensional arrays of numbers.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] Matrices, subject to certain requirements tend to form groups known as matrix groups.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] Similarly under certain conditions matrices form rings known as matrix rings.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] Though the product of matrices is not in general commutative, certain matrices form fields sometimes called matrix fields.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] The objects of this category are natural numbers, representing the dimensions of the matrices.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] This article focuses on matrices whose entries are real or complex numbers.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] However, matrices can be considered with much more general types of entries than real or complex numbers.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] As a first step of generalization, any field, that is, a set where addition, subtraction, multiplication, and division operations are defined and well-behaved, may be used instead of ⁠ $\mathbb {R}$ ⁠ or ⁠ $\mathbb {C}$ ⁠, for example rational numbers or finite fields.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] For example, coding theory makes use of matrices over finite fields.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] Wherever eigenvalues are considered, as these are roots of a polynomial, they may exist only in a larger field than that of the entries of the matrix.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] For instance, they may be complex in the case of a matrix with real entries.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] The possibility to reinterpret the entries of a matrix as elements of a larger field (for example, to view a real matrix as a complex matrix whose entries happen to be all real) then allows considering each square matrix to possess a full set of eigenvalues.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] Alternatively one can consider only matrices with entries in an algebraically closed field, such as ⁠ $\mathbb {C} ,$ ⁠ from the outset.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] Matrices whose entries are polynomials, and more generally, matrices with entries in a ring R are widely used in mathematics.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] Rings are a more general notion than fields in that a division operation need not exist.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] The very same addition and multiplication operations of matrices extend to this setting, too.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] The set M(*n*, *R*) (also denoted M*n*(R)) of all square n-by-n matrices over R is a ring called matrix ring, isomorphic to the endomorphism ring of the left R-module Rn.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] If the ring R is commutative, that is, its multiplication is commutative, then the ring M(*n*, *R*) is also an associative algebra over *R*.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] The determinant of square matrices over a commutative ring R can still be defined using the Leibniz formula; such a matrix is invertible if and only if its determinant is invertible in R, generalizing the situation over a field F, where every nonzero element is invertible.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] Matrices over superrings are called supermatrices.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] Matrices do not always have all their entries in the same ring – or even in any ring at all.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] One special but common case is block matrices, which may be considered as matrices whose entries themselves are matrices.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] The entries need not be square matrices, and thus need not be members of any ring; but in order to multiply them, their sizes must fulfill certain conditions: each pair of submatrices that are multiplied in forming the overall product must have compatible sizes.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] Linear maps $\mathbb {R} ^{n}\to \mathbb {R} ^{m}$ are equivalent to m-by-n matrices, as described above.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] The matrix depends on the choice of the bases: different choices of bases give rise to different, but equivalent matrices.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] Many of the above concrete notions can be reinterpreted in this light, for example, the transpose matrix **A**T describes the transpose of the linear map given by **A**, concerning the dual bases.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] These properties can be restated more naturally: the category of matrices with entries in a field k with multiplication as composition is equivalent to the category of finite-dimensional vector spaces and linear maps over this field.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] More generally, the set of m × n matrices can be used to represent the R-linear maps between the free modules Rm and Rn for an arbitrary ring R with unity.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] When *n* = *m* composition of these maps is possible, and this gives rise to the matrix ring of n × n matrices representing the endomorphism ring of Rn.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] A group is a mathematical structure consisting of a set of objects together with a binary operation, that is, an operation combining any two objects to a third, subject to certain requirements.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] A group in which the objects are invertible ⁠ $n\times n$ ⁠ matrices and the group operation is matrix multiplication is called a *matrix group* of degree ⁠ n ⁠.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] Every such matrix group is a subgroup of (that is, a smaller group contained within) the group of *all* invertible ⁠ $n\times n$ ⁠ matrices, the general linear group of degree ⁠ n ⁠.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] Any property of square matrices that is preserved under matrix products and inverses can be used to define a matrix group.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] For example, the set of all ⁠ $n\times n$ ⁠ matrices whose determinant is 1 form a group called the special linear group of degree ⁠ n ⁠.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] The set of orthogonal matrices, determined by the condition ${\mathbf {M}}^{\rm {T}}{\mathbf {M}}={\mathbf {I}},$ form the orthogonal group.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] Every orthogonal matrix has determinant 1 or −1.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] Orthogonal matrices with determinant 1 form a group called the *special orthogonal group*.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] Every finite group is isomorphic to a matrix group, as one can see by considering the regular representation of the symmetric group.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] General groups can be studied using matrix groups, which are comparatively well understood, using representation theory.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] It is also possible to consider matrices with infinitely many rows and columns.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] The basic operations introduced above are defined the same way in this case.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] Matrix multiplication, however, and all operations stemming therefrom are only meaningful when restricted to certain matrices, since the sum featuring in the above definition of the matrix product will contain an infinity of summands.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] An easy way to circumvent this issue is to restrict to *finitary matrices* all of whose rows (or columns) contain only finitely many nonzero terms.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] As in the finite case (see above), where matrices describe linear maps, infinite matrices can be used to describe operators on Hilbert spaces, where convergence and continuity questions arise.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] However, the explicit point of view of matrices tends to obfuscate the matter, and the abstract and more powerful tools of functional analysis are used instead, by relating matrices to linear maps (as in the finite case above), but imposing additional convergence and continuity constraints.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] An *empty matrix* is a matrix in which the number of rows or columns (or both) is zero.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] Empty matrices can be a useful base case for certain recursive constructions, and can help to deal with maps involving the zero vector space.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] For example, if **A** is a 3 × 0 matrix and **B** is a 0 × 3 matrix, then **AB** is the 3 × 3 zero matrix corresponding to the null map from a 3-dimensional space V to itself, while **BA** is a 0 × 0 matrix.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] There is no common notation for empty matrices, but most computer algebra systems allow creating and computing with them.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] The determinant of the 0 × 0 matrix is conventionally defined to be 1, consistent with the empty product occurring in the Leibniz formula for the determinant.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] This value is also needed for consistency with the 2 × 2 case of the Desnanot–Jacobi identity relating determinants to the determinants of smaller matrices.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] A semiring is similar to a ring, but elements need not have additive inverses, therefore one cannot do subtraction freely there.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] The definition of addition and multiplication of matrices with entries in a ring applies to matrices with entries in a semiring without modification.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] Matrices of fixed size with entries in a semiring form a commutative monoid $\operatorname {Mat} (m,n;R)$ under addition.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] Square matrices of fixed size with entries in a semiring form a semiring $\operatorname {Mat} (n;R)$ under addition and multiplication.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] The determinant of an n × n square matrix M with entries in a commutative semiring R cannot be defined in general because the definition would involve additive inverses of semiring elements.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] where the sums are taken over even permutations and odd permutations, respectively.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] Matrices and their multiplication can be defined with entries objects of a category equipped with a "tensor product" similar to multiplication in a ring, having coproducts similar to addition in a ring, in that the former is distributive over the latter.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] However, the multiplication thus defined may be only associative in a sense weaker than usual.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] These are part of a bigger structure called the *bicategory of matrices*.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] The complete description of the above summary for interested readers follows.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] In general, the bicategory of matrices need not be a strict 2-category.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p01] For example, the composition of 1-morphisms may not be associative in the usual strict sense, but only up to coherent isomorphism.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p02] There are numerous applications of matrices, both in mathematics and other sciences.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p02] Some of them merely take advantage of the compact representation of a set of numbers in a matrix.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p02] For example, text mining and automated thesaurus compilation makes use of document-term matrices such as tf-idf to track frequencies of certain words in several documents.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p02] Complex numbers can be represented by particular real 2-by-2 matrices via $a+ib\leftrightarrow {\begin{bmatrix}a&-b\\b&a\end{bmatrix}},$ under which addition and multiplication of complex numbers and matrices correspond to each other.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p02] For example, 2-by-2 rotation matrices represent the multiplication with some complex number of absolute value 1, as above.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p02] A similar interpretation is possible for quaternions and Clifford algebras in general.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p02] In game theory and economics, the payoff matrix encodes the payoff for two players, depending on which out of a given (finite) set of strategies the players choose.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p02] The expected outcome of the game, when both players play mixed strategies, is obtained by multiplying this matrix on both sides by vectors representing the strategies.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p02] The minimax theorem central to game theory is closely related to the duality theory of linear programs, which are often formulated in terms of matrix-vector products.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p02] Early encryption techniques such as the Hill cipher also used matrices.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p02] However, due to the linear nature of matrices, these codes are comparatively easy to break.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p02] Matrices over a polynomial ring are important in the study of control theory.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p02] Chemistry makes use of matrices in various ways, particularly since the use of quantum theory to discuss molecular bonding and spectroscopy.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p02] Examples are the overlap matrix and the Fock matrix used in solving the Roothaan equations to obtain the molecular orbitals of the Hartree–Fock method.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p02] The adjacency matrix of a finite graph is a basic notion of graph theory.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p02] It records which vertices of the graph are connected by an edge.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p02] Matrices containing just two different values (1 and 0 meaning for example "yes" and "no", respectively) are called logical matrices.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p02] The distance (or cost) matrix contains information about the distances of the edges.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p02] These concepts can be applied to websites connected by hyperlinks, or cities connected by roads etc., in which case (unless the connection network is extremely dense) the matrices tend to be sparse, that is, contain few nonzero entries.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p02] Therefore, specifically tailored matrix algorithms can be used in network theory.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p02] It encodes information about the local growth behavior of the function: given a critical point **x** = (*x*1, ..., *xn*), that is, a point where the first partial derivatives $\partial f/\partial x_{i}$ of f vanish, the function has a local minimum if the Hessian matrix is positive definite.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p02] Quadratic programming can be used to find global minima or maxima of quadratic functions closely related to the ones attached to matrices (see above).
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p02] Another matrix frequently used in geometrical situations is the Jacobi matrix of a differentiable map ⁠ $f:\mathbb {R} ^{n}\to \mathbb {R} ^{m}$ ⁠.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p02] Partial differential equations can be classified by considering the matrix of coefficients of the highest-order differential operators of the equation.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p02] For elliptic partial differential equations this matrix is positive definite, which has a decisive influence on the set of possible solutions of the equation in question.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p02] The finite element method is an important numerical method to solve partial differential equations, widely applied in simulating complex physical systems.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p02] It attempts to approximate the solution to some equation by piecewise linear functions, where the pieces are chosen concerning a sufficiently fine grid, which in turn can be recast as a matrix equation.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p02] Stochastic matrices are square matrices whose rows are probability vectors, that is, whose entries are non-negative and sum up to one.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p02] Stochastic matrices are used to define Markov chains with finitely many states.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p02] A row of the stochastic matrix gives the probability distribution for the next position of some particle currently in the state that corresponds to the row.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p02] Properties of the Markov chain—like absorbing states, that is, states that any particle attains eventually—can be read off the eigenvectors of the transition matrices.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p02] Statistics also makes use of matrices in many different forms.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p02] Descriptive statistics is concerned with describing data sets, which can often be represented as data matrices, which may then be subjected to dimensionality reduction techniques.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p02] The covariance matrix encodes the mutual variance of several random variables.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p02] Random matrices are matrices whose entries are random numbers, subject to suitable probability distributions, such as matrix normal distribution.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p02] Beyond probability theory, they are applied in domains ranging from number theory to physics.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p02] The first model of quantum mechanics (Heisenberg, 1925) used infinite-dimensional matrices to define the operators that took over the role of variables like position, momentum and energy from classical physics.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p02] (This is sometimes referred to as matrix mechanics.) Matrices, both finite and infinite-dimensional, have since been employed for many purposes in quantum mechanics.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p02] One particular example is the density matrix, a tool used in calculating the probabilities of the outcomes of measurements performed on physical systems.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p02] Linear transformations and the associated symmetries play a key role in modern physics.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p02] For example, elementary particles in quantum field theory are classified as representations of the Lorentz group of special relativity and, more specifically, by their behavior under the spin group.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p02] Concrete representations involving the Pauli matrices and more general gamma matrices are an integral part of the physical description of fermions, which behave as spinors.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p02] The Cabibbo–Kobayashi–Maskawa matrix, in turn, expresses the fact that the basic quark states that are important for weak interactions are not the same as, but linearly related to the basic quark states that define particles with specific and distinct masses.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p02] The linear combination is given by a matrix known as the S-matrix, which encodes all information about the possible interactions between particles.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p02] A general application of matrices in physics is the description of linearly coupled harmonic systems.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p02] The equations of motion of such systems can be described in matrix form, with a mass matrix multiplying a generalized velocity to give the kinetic term, and a force matrix multiplying a displacement vector to characterize the interactions.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p02] The best way to obtain solutions is to determine the system's eigenvectors, its normal modes, by diagonalizing the matrix equation.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p02] Techniques like this are crucial when it comes to the internal dynamics of molecules: the internal vibrations of systems consisting of mutually bound component atoms.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p02] They are also needed for describing mechanical vibrations, and oscillations in electrical circuits.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p02] Geometrical optics provides further matrix applications.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p02] In this approximative theory, the wave nature of light is neglected.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p02] The result is a model in which light rays are indeed geometrical rays.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p02] There are two kinds of matrices, viz. a *refraction matrix* describing the refraction at a lens surface, and a *translation matrix*, describing the translation of the plane of reference to the next refracting surface, where another refraction matrix applies.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p02] The optical system, consisting of a combination of lenses and reflective elements, is simply described by the matrix resulting from the product of the components' matrices.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p02] The Jones calculus models the polarization of a light source as a $2\times 2$ vector, and the effects of optical filters on this polarization vector as a matrix.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p02] Matrices have a long history of application in solving linear equations but they were known as arrays until the 1800s.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p02] The Chinese text *The Nine Chapters on the Mathematical Art* written in the 10th–2nd century BCE is the first example of the use of array methods to solve simultaneous equations.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p02] In 1545 Italian mathematician Gerolamo Cardano introduced the method to Europe when he published *Ars Magna*.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p02] The Japanese mathematician Seki used the same array methods to solve simultaneous equations in 1683.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p02] The Dutch mathematicianJan de Witt represented transformations using arrays in his 1659 book *Elements of Curves* (1659).
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p02] Between 1700 and 1710 Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz publicized the use of arrays for recording information or solutions and experimented with over 50 different systems of arrays.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p02] Arthur Cayley published a treatise on geometric transformations using matrices that were not rotated versions of the coefficients being investigated as had previously been done.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p02] Instead, he defined operations such as addition, subtraction, multiplication, and division as transformations of those matrices and showed the associative and distributive properties held.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p02] Cayley investigated and demonstrated the non-commutative property of matrix multiplication as well as the commutative property of matrix addition.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p02] Early matrix theory had limited the use of arrays almost exclusively to determinants and Cayley's abstract matrix operations were revolutionary.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p02] He was instrumental in proposing a matrix concept independent of equation systems.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p02] In 1858, Cayley published his *A memoir on the theory of matrices* in which he proposed and demonstrated the Cayley–Hamilton theorem.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p02] The English mathematician Cuthbert Edmund Cullis was the first to use modern bracket notation for matrices in 1913 and he simultaneously demonstrated the first significant use of the notation **A** = [*a**i*,*j*] to represent a matrix where *a**i*,*j* refers to the ith row and the jth column.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p02] The modern study of determinants sprang from several sources.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p02] Number-theoretical problems led Gauss to relate coefficients of quadratic forms, that is, expressions such as *x*2 + *xy* − 2*y*2, and linear maps in three dimensions to matrices.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p02] Eisenstein further developed these notions, including the remark that, in modern parlance, matrix products are non-commutative.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p02] He also showed, in 1829, that the eigenvalues of symmetric matrices are real.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p02] Jacobi studied "functional determinants"—later called Jacobi determinants by Sylvester—which can be used to describe geometric transformations at a local (or infinitesimal) level, see above.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p02] Kronecker's *Vorlesungen über die Theorie der Determinanten* and Weierstrass's *Zur Determinantentheorie*, both published in 1903, first treated determinants axiomatically, as opposed to previous more concrete approaches such as the mentioned formula of Cauchy.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p02] At that point, determinants were firmly established.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p02] Many theorems were first established for small matrices only, for example, the Cayley–Hamilton theorem was proved for 2 × 2 matrices by Cayley in the aforementioned memoir, and by Hamilton for 4 × 4 matrices.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p02] Frobenius, working on bilinear forms, generalized the theorem to all dimensions (1898).
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p02] Also at the end of the 19th century, the Gauss–Jordan elimination (generalizing a special case now known as Gauss elimination) was established by Wilhelm Jordan.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p02] In the early 20th century, matrices attained a central role in linear algebra, partially due to their use in the classification of the hypercomplex number systems of the previous century.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p02] The inception of matrix mechanics by Heisenberg, Born and Jordan led to studying matrices with infinitely many rows and columns.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p02] Later, von Neumann carried out the mathematical formulation of quantum mechanics, by further developing functional analytic notions such as linear operators on Hilbert spaces, which, very roughly speaking, correspond to Euclidean space, but with an infinity of independent directions.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p02] The word has been used in unusual ways by at least two authors of historical importance.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p02] Bertrand Russell and Alfred North Whitehead in their *Principia Mathematica* (1910–1913) use the word "matrix" in the context of their axiom of reducibility.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p02] For example, a function Φ(*x*, *y*) of two variables x and y can be reduced to a *collection* of functions of a single variable, such as y, by "considering" the function for all possible values of "individuals" ai substituted in place of a variable x.
[src:numpy-arrays/matrix-mathematics-p02] Alfred Tarski in his 1941 *Introduction to Logic* used the word "matrix" synonymously with the notion of truth table as used in mathematical logic.
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] Numerical analysis finds application in all fields of engineering and the physical sciences, and in the 21st century also the life and social sciences like economics, medicine, business and even the arts.
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] Current growth in computing power has enabled the use of more complex numerical analysis, providing detailed and realistic mathematical models in science and engineering.
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] Before modern computers, numerical methods often relied on hand interpolation formulas, using data from large printed tables.
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] Since the mid-20th century, computers calculate the required functions instead, but many of the same formulas continue to be used in software algorithms.
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] The numerical point of view goes back to the earliest mathematical writings.
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] A tablet from the Yale Babylonian Collection (YBC 7289), gives a sexagesimal numerical approximation of the square root of 2, the length of the diagonal in a unit square.
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] Numerical analysis continues this long tradition: rather than giving exact symbolic answers translated into digits and applicable only to real-world measurements, approximate solutions within specified error bounds are used.
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] The field of numerical analysis predates the invention of modern computers by many centuries.
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] Linear interpolation was already in use more than 2000 years ago.
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] Many great mathematicians of the past were preoccupied by numerical analysis, as is obvious from the names of important algorithms like Newton's method, Lagrange interpolation polynomial, Gaussian elimination, or Euler's method.
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] The origins of modern numerical analysis are often linked to a 1947 paper by John von Neumann and Herman Goldstine, but others consider modern numerical analysis to go back to work by E.
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] To facilitate computations by hand, large books were produced with formulas and tables of data such as interpolation points and function coefficients.
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] Using these tables, often calculated out to 16 decimal places or more for some functions, one could look up values to plug into the formulas given and achieve very good numerical estimates of some functions.
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] The canonical work in the field is the NIST publication edited by Abramowitz and Stegun, a 1000-plus page book of a very large number of commonly used formulas and functions and their values at many points.
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] The function values are no longer very useful when a computer is available, but the large listing of formulas can still be very handy.
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] The mechanical calculator was also developed as a tool for hand computation.
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] These calculators evolved into electronic computers in the 1940s, and it was then found that these computers were also useful for administrative purposes.
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] But the invention of the computer also influenced the field of numerical analysis, since now longer and more complicated calculations could be done.
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] The Leslie Fox Prize for Numerical Analysis was initiated in 1985 by the Institute of Mathematics and its Applications.
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] Direct methods compute the solution to a problem in a finite number of steps.
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] These methods would give the precise answer if they were performed in infinite precision arithmetic.
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] Examples include Gaussian elimination, the QR factorization method for solving systems of linear equations, and the simplex method of linear programming.
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] In practice, finite precision is used and the result is an approximation of the true solution (assuming stability).
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] In contrast to direct methods, iterative methods are not expected to terminate in a finite number of steps, even if infinite precision were possible.
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] Starting from an initial guess, iterative methods form successive approximations that converge to the exact solution only in the limit.
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] A convergence test, often involving the residual, is specified in order to decide when a sufficiently accurate solution has (hopefully) been found.
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] Even using infinite precision arithmetic these methods would not reach the solution within a finite number of steps (in general).
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] Examples include Newton's method, the bisection method, and Jacobi iteration.
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] In computational matrix algebra, iterative methods are generally needed for large problems.
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] Iterative methods are more common than direct methods in numerical analysis.
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] Some methods are direct in principle but are usually used as though they were not, e.g.
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] GMRES and the conjugate gradient method.
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] For these methods the number of steps needed to obtain the exact solution is so large that an approximation is accepted in the same manner as for an iterative method.
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] For the iterative method, apply the bisection method to *f*(*x*) = 3*x*3 − 24.
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] From this table it can be concluded that the solution is between 1.875 and 2.0625.
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] The algorithm might return any number in that range with an error less than 0.2.
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] Ill-conditioned problem: Take the function *f*(*x*) = 1/(*x* − 1).
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] Evaluating *f*(*x*) near *x* = 1 is an ill-conditioned problem.
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] Well-conditioned problem: By contrast, evaluating the same function *f*(*x*) = 1/(*x* − 1) near *x* = 10 is a well-conditioned problem.
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] Furthermore, continuous problems must sometimes be replaced by a discrete problem whose solution is known to approximate that of the continuous problem; this process is called 'discretization'.
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] For example, the solution of a differential equation is a function.
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] This function must be represented by a finite amount of data, for instance by its value at a finite number of points at its domain, even though this domain is a continuum.
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] The study of errors forms an important part of numerical analysis.
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] There are several ways in which error can be introduced in the solution of the problem.
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] Round-off errors arise because it is impossible to represent all real numbers exactly on a machine with finite memory (which is what all practical digital computers are).
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] Truncation errors are committed when an iterative method is terminated or a mathematical procedure is approximated and the approximate solution differs from the exact solution.
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] Similarly, discretization induces a discretization error because the solution of the discrete problem does not coincide with the solution of the continuous problem.
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] In the example above to compute the solution of $3x^{3}+4=28$ , after ten iterations, the calculated root is roughly 1.99.
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] Therefore, the truncation error is roughly 0.01.
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] Once an error is generated, it propagates through the calculation.
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] For example, the operation + on a computer is inexact.
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] A calculation of the type ⁠ $a+b+c+d+e$ ⁠ is even more inexact.
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] A truncation error is created when a mathematical procedure is approximated.
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] To integrate a function exactly, an infinite sum of regions must be found, but numerically only a finite sum of regions can be found, and hence the approximation of the exact solution.
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] Similarly, to differentiate a function, the differential element approaches zero, but numerically only a nonzero value of the differential element can be chosen.
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] An algorithm is called *numerically stable* if an error, whatever its cause, does not grow to be much larger during the calculation.
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] This happens if the problem is *well-conditioned*, meaning that the solution changes by only a small amount if the problem data are changed by a small amount.
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] To the contrary, if a problem is 'ill-conditioned', then any small error in the data will grow to be a large error.
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] Both the original problem and the algorithm used to solve that problem can be well-conditioned or ill-conditioned, and any combination is possible.
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] So an algorithm that solves a well-conditioned problem may be either numerically stable or numerically unstable.
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] An art of numerical analysis is to find a stable algorithm for solving a well-posed mathematical problem.
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] The field of numerical analysis includes many sub-disciplines.
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] One of the simplest problems is the evaluation of a function at a given point.
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] The most straightforward approach, of just plugging in the number in the formula is sometimes not very efficient.
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] For polynomials, a better approach is using the Horner scheme, since it reduces the necessary number of multiplications and additions.
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] Generally, it is important to estimate and control round-off errors arising from the use of floating-point arithmetic.
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] Interpolation solves the following problem: given the value of some unknown function at a number of points, what value does that function have at some other point between the given points?
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] Extrapolation is very similar to interpolation, except that now the value of the unknown function at a point which is outside the given points must be found.
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] Regression is also similar, but it takes into account that the data are imprecise.
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] Given some points, and a measurement of the value of some function at these points (with an error), the unknown function can be found.
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] The least squares-method is one way to achieve this.
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] Another fundamental problem is computing the solution of some given equation.
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] Two cases are commonly distinguished, depending on whether the equation is linear or not.
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] For instance, the equation $2x+5=3$ is linear while $2x^{2}+5=3$ is not.
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] Much effort has been put in the development of methods for solving systems of linear equations.
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] Standard direct methods, i.e., methods that use some matrix decomposition are Gaussian elimination, LU decomposition, Cholesky decomposition for symmetric (or hermitian) and positive-definite matrix, and QR decomposition for non-square matrices.
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] Iterative methods such as the Jacobi method, Gauss–Seidel method, successive over-relaxation and conjugate gradient method are usually preferred for large systems.
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] General iterative methods can be developed using a matrix splitting.
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] Root-finding algorithms are used to solve nonlinear equations (they are so named since a root of a function is an argument for which the function yields zero).
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] If the function is differentiable and the derivative is known, then Newton's method is a popular choice.
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] Linearization is another technique for solving nonlinear equations.
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] Several important problems can be phrased in terms of eigenvalue decompositions or singular value decompositions.
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] For instance, the spectral image compression algorithm is based on the singular value decomposition.
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] The corresponding tool in statistics is called principal component analysis.
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] Optimization problems ask for the point at which a given function is maximized (or minimized).
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] Often, the point also has to satisfy some constraints.
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] The field of optimization is further split in several subfields, depending on the form of the objective function and the constraint.
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] For instance, linear programming deals with the case that both the objective function and the constraints are linear.
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] A famous method in linear programming is the simplex method.
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] The method of Lagrange multipliers can be used to reduce optimization problems with constraints to unconstrained optimization problems.
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] Numerical integration, in some instances also known as numerical quadrature, asks for the value of a definite integral.
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] Popular methods use one of the Newton–Cotes formulas (like the midpoint rule or Simpson's rule) or Gaussian quadrature.
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] These methods rely on a "divide and conquer" strategy, whereby an integral on a relatively large set is broken down into integrals on smaller sets.
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] In higher dimensions, where these methods become prohibitively expensive in terms of computational effort, one may use Monte Carlo or quasi-Monte Carlo methods (see Monte Carlo integration), or, in modestly large dimensions, the method of sparse grids.
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] Numerical analysis is also concerned with computing (in an approximate way) the solution of differential equations, both ordinary differential equations and partial differential equations.
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] Partial differential equations are solved by first discretizing the equation, bringing it into a finite-dimensional subspace.
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] This can be done by a finite element method, a finite difference method, or (particularly in engineering) a finite volume method.
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] The theoretical justification of these methods often involves theorems from functional analysis.
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] This reduces the problem to the solution of an algebraic equation.
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] Since the late twentieth century, most algorithms are implemented in a variety of programming languages.
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] The Netlib repository contains various collections of software routines for numerical problems, mostly in Fortran and C.
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] Commercial products implementing many different numerical algorithms include the IMSL and NAG libraries; a free-software alternative is the GNU Scientific Library.
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] Over the years the Royal Statistical Society published numerous algorithms in its *Applied Statistics* (code for these "AS" functions is here); ACM similarly, in its *Transactions on Mathematical Software* ("TOMS" code is here).
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] The Naval Surface Warfare Center several times published its *Library of Mathematics Subroutines* (code here).
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] There are several popular numerical computing applications such as MATLAB, TK Solver, S-PLUS, and IDL as well as free and open-source alternatives such as FreeMat, Scilab, GNU Octave (similar to Matlab), and IT++ (a C++ library).
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] There are also programming languages such as R (similar to S-PLUS), Julia, and Python with libraries such as NumPy, SciPy and SymPy.
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] Performance varies widely: while vector and matrix operations are usually fast, scalar loops may vary in speed by more than an order of magnitude.
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] Many computer algebra systems such as Mathematica also benefit from the availability of arbitrary-precision arithmetic which can provide more accurate results.
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] Also, any spreadsheet software can be used to solve simple problems relating to numerical analysis.
[src:numpy-arrays/numerical-analysis] Excel, for example, has hundreds of available functions, including for matrices, which may be used in conjunction with its built in "solver".
[src:numpy-arrays/numpy] The Python programming language was not originally designed for numerical computing, but attracted the attention of the scientific and engineering community early on.
[src:numpy-arrays/numpy] In 1995 the special interest group (SIG) *matrix-sig* was founded with the aim of defining an array computing package; among its members was Python designer and maintainer Guido van Rossum, who extended Python's syntax (in particular the indexing syntax) to make array computing easier.
[src:numpy-arrays/numpy] Hugunin, a graduate student at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT), joined the Corporation for National Research Initiatives (CNRI) in 1997 to work on JPython, leaving Paul Dubois of Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory (LLNL) to take over as maintainer.
[src:numpy-arrays/numpy] Other early contributors include David Ascher, Konrad Hinsen and Travis Oliphant.
[src:numpy-arrays/numpy] A new package called *Numarray* was written as a more flexible replacement for Numeric.
[src:numpy-arrays/numpy] Numarray had faster operations for large arrays, but was slower than Numeric on small ones, so for a time both packages were used in parallel for different use cases.
[src:numpy-arrays/numpy] The last version of Numeric (v24.2) was released on 11 November 2005, while the last version of numarray (v1.5.2) was released on 24 August 2006.
[src:numpy-arrays/numpy] There was a desire to get Numeric into the Python standard library, but Guido van Rossum decided that the code was not maintainable in its state then.
[src:numpy-arrays/numpy] In early 2005, NumPy developer Travis Oliphant wanted to unify the community around a single array package and ported Numarray's features to Numeric, releasing the result as NumPy 1.0 in 2006.
[src:numpy-arrays/numpy] To avoid installing the large SciPy package just to get an array object, this new package was separated and called NumPy.
[src:numpy-arrays/numpy] Support for Python 3 was added in 2011 with NumPy version 1.5.0.
[src:numpy-arrays/numpy] In 2011, PyPy started development on an implementation of the NumPy API for PyPy.
[src:numpy-arrays/numpy] As of 2023, it is not yet fully compatible with NumPy.
[src:numpy-arrays/numpy] NumPy targets the CPython reference implementation of Python, which is a non-optimizing bytecode interpreter.
[src:numpy-arrays/numpy] Mathematical algorithms written for this version of Python often run much slower than compiled equivalents due to the absence of compiler optimization.
[src:numpy-arrays/numpy] NumPy addresses the slowness problem partly by providing multidimensional arrays and functions and operators that operate efficiently on arrays; using these requires rewriting some code, mostly inner loops, using NumPy.
[src:numpy-arrays/numpy] Using NumPy in Python gives functionality comparable to MATLAB since they are both interpreted, and they both allow the user to write fast programs as long as most operations work on arrays or matrices instead of scalars.
[src:numpy-arrays/numpy] In comparison, MATLAB boasts a large number of additional toolboxes, notably Simulink, whereas NumPy is intrinsically integrated with Python, a more modern and complete programming language.
[src:numpy-arrays/numpy] Moreover, complementary Python packages are available; SciPy is a library that adds more MATLAB-like functionality and Matplotlib is a plotting package that provides MATLAB-like plotting functionality.
[src:numpy-arrays/numpy] Although MATLAB can perform sparse matrix operations, NumPy alone cannot perform such operations and requires the use of the scipy.sparse library.
[src:numpy-arrays/numpy] Internally, both MATLAB and NumPy rely on BLAS and LAPACK for efficient linear algebra computations.
[src:numpy-arrays/numpy] Python bindings of the widely used computer vision library OpenCV utilize NumPy arrays to store and operate on data.
[src:numpy-arrays/numpy] Since images with multiple channels are simply represented as three-dimensional arrays, indexing, slicing or masking with other arrays are very efficient ways to access specific pixels of an image.
[src:numpy-arrays/numpy] The NumPy array as universal data structure in OpenCV for images, extracted feature points, filter kernels and many more vastly simplifies the programming workflow and debugging.
[src:numpy-arrays/numpy] Importantly, many NumPy operations release the global interpreter lock, which allows for multithreaded processing.
[src:numpy-arrays/numpy] NumPy also provides a C API, which allows Python code to interoperate with external libraries written in low-level languages.
[src:numpy-arrays/numpy] The core functionality of NumPy is its "ndarray", for *n*-dimensional array, data structure.
[src:numpy-arrays/numpy] These arrays are strided views on memory.
[src:numpy-arrays/numpy] In contrast to Python's built-in list data structure, these arrays are homogeneously typed: all elements of a single array must be of the same type.
[src:numpy-arrays/numpy] Such arrays can also be views into memory buffers allocated by C/C++, Python, and Fortran extensions to the CPython interpreter without the need to copy data around, giving a degree of compatibility with existing numerical libraries.
[src:numpy-arrays/numpy] This functionality is exploited by the SciPy package, which wraps a number of such libraries (notably BLAS and LAPACK).
[src:numpy-arrays/numpy] NumPy has built-in support for memory-mapped ndarrays.
[src:numpy-arrays/numpy] Inserting or appending entries to an array is not as trivially possible as it is with Python's lists.
[src:numpy-arrays/numpy] The `np.pad(...)` routine to extend arrays actually creates new arrays of the desired shape and padding values, copies the given array into the new one and returns it.
[src:numpy-arrays/numpy] NumPy's `np.concatenate([a1,a2])` operation does not actually link the two arrays but returns a new one, filled with the entries from both given arrays in sequence.
[src:numpy-arrays/numpy] Reshaping the dimensionality of an array with `np.reshape(...)` is only possible as long as the number of elements in the array does not change.
[src:numpy-arrays/numpy] These circumstances originate from the fact that NumPy's arrays must be views on contiguous memory buffers.
[src:numpy-arrays/numpy] Runtime compilation of numerical code has been implemented by several groups to avoid these problems; open source solutions that interoperate with NumPy include numexpr and Numba.
[src:numpy-arrays/numpy] Cython and Pythran are static-compiling alternatives to these.
[src:numpy-arrays/numpy] Many modern large-scale scientific computing applications have requirements that exceed the capabilities of the NumPy arrays.
[src:numpy-arrays/numpy] For example, NumPy arrays are usually loaded into a computer's memory, which might have insufficient capacity for the analysis of large datasets.
[src:numpy-arrays/numpy] Further, NumPy operations are executed on a single CPU.
[src:numpy-arrays/numpy] However, many linear algebra operations can be accelerated by executing them on clusters of CPUs or on specialized hardware, such as GPUs and TPUs, which many deep learning applications rely on.
[src:numpy-arrays/numpy] As a result, several alternative array implementations have arisen in the scientific python ecosystem over the recent years, such as Dask for distributed arrays and TensorFlow or JAX for computations on GPUs.
[src:numpy-arrays/numpy] Because of its popularity, these often implement a subset of NumPy's API or mimic it, so that users can change their array implementation with minimal changes to their code required.
[src:numpy-arrays/numpy] A library named CuPy, accelerated by Nvidia's CUDA framework, has also shown potential for faster computing, being a 'drop-in replacement' of NumPy.
[src:numpy-arrays/numpy] NumPy is conventionally imported as `np`.
[src:numpy-arrays/numpy] Functional Python and vectorized NumPy version.
[src:numpy-arrays/numpy] Quickly wrap native code for faster scripts.
[src:numpy-arrays/row-and-column-major-order] In computing, **row-major order** and **column-major order** are methods for storing multidimensional arrays in linear storage such as random access memory.
[src:numpy-arrays/row-and-column-major-order] The difference between the orders lies in which elements of an array are contiguous in memory.
[src:numpy-arrays/row-and-column-major-order] In row-major order, the consecutive elements of a row reside next to each other, whereas the same holds true for consecutive elements of a column in column-major order.
[src:numpy-arrays/row-and-column-major-order] While the terms allude to the rows and columns of a two-dimensional array, i.e. a matrix, the orders can be generalized to arrays of any dimension by noting that the terms row-major and column-major are equivalent to lexicographic and colexicographic orders, respectively.
[src:numpy-arrays/row-and-column-major-order] Matrices, being commonly represented as collections of row or column vectors, using this approach are effectively stored as consecutive vectors or consecutive vector components.
[src:numpy-arrays/row-and-column-major-order] Such ways of storing data are referred to as AoS and SoA respectively.
[src:numpy-arrays/row-and-column-major-order] Data layout is critical for correctly passing arrays between programs written in different programming languages.
[src:numpy-arrays/row-and-column-major-order] It is also important for performance when traversing an array because modern CPUs process sequential data more efficiently than nonsequential data.
[src:numpy-arrays/row-and-column-major-order] This is primarily due to CPU caching which exploits spatial locality of reference.
[src:numpy-arrays/row-and-column-major-order] In addition, contiguous access makes it possible to use SIMD instructions that operate on vectors of data.
[src:numpy-arrays/row-and-column-major-order] In some media such as magnetic-tape data storage, accessing sequentially is orders of magnitude faster than nonsequential access.
[src:numpy-arrays/row-and-column-major-order] The terms row-major and column-major stem from the terminology related to ordering objects.
[src:numpy-arrays/row-and-column-major-order] A general way to order objects with many attributes is to first group and order them by one attribute, and then, within each such group, group and order them by another attribute, etc.
[src:numpy-arrays/row-and-column-major-order] If more than one attribute participates in ordering, the first would be called *major* and the last *minor*.
[src:numpy-arrays/row-and-column-major-order] If two attributes participate in ordering, it is sufficient to name only the major attribute.
[src:numpy-arrays/row-and-column-major-order] In the case of arrays, the attributes are the indices along each dimension.
[src:numpy-arrays/row-and-column-major-order] For matrices in mathematical notation, the first index indicates the *row*, and the second indicates the *column*, e.g., given a matrix A , the entry $a_{1,2}$ is in its first row and second column.
[src:numpy-arrays/row-and-column-major-order] This convention is carried over to the syntax in programming languages, although often with indexes starting at 0 instead of 1.
[src:numpy-arrays/row-and-column-major-order] Even though the row is indicated by the *first* index and the column by the *second* index, no grouping order between the dimensions is implied by this.
[src:numpy-arrays/row-and-column-major-order] The choice of how to group and order the indices, either by row-major or column-major methods, is thus a matter of convention.
[src:numpy-arrays/row-and-column-major-order] The same terminology can be applied to even higher dimensional arrays.
[src:numpy-arrays/row-and-column-major-order] Row-major grouping starts from the *leftmost* index and column-major from the *rightmost* index, leading to lexicographic and colexicographic (or colex) orders, respectively.
[src:numpy-arrays/row-and-column-major-order] Programming languages handle this in different ways.
[src:numpy-arrays/row-and-column-major-order] Running the loop row-wise is preferred in row-major languages like C and vice versa for column-major languages.
[src:numpy-arrays/row-and-column-major-order] Programming languages or their standard libraries that support multi-dimensional arrays typically have a native row-major or column-major storage order for these arrays.
[src:numpy-arrays/row-and-column-major-order] Row-major order is used in C/C++/Objective-C (for C-style arrays), PL/I, Pascal, Speakeasy, and SAS.
[src:numpy-arrays/row-and-column-major-order] Column-major order is used in Fortran, IDL, MATLAB, GNU Octave, Julia, S, S-PLUS, R, Scilab, Yorick, and Rasdaman.
[src:numpy-arrays/row-and-column-major-order] A typical alternative for dense array storage is to use Iliffe vectors, which typically store pointers to elements in the same row contiguously (like row-major order), but not the rows themselves.
[src:numpy-arrays/row-and-column-major-order] They are used in (ordered by age): Java, C#/CLI/.Net, Scala, and Swift.
[src:numpy-arrays/row-and-column-major-order] Even less dense is to use lists of lists, e.g., in Python, and in the Wolfram Language of Wolfram Mathematica.
[src:numpy-arrays/row-and-column-major-order] An alternative approach uses tables of tables, e.g., in Lua.
[src:numpy-arrays/row-and-column-major-order] Support for multi-dimensional arrays may also be provided by external libraries, which may even support arbitrary orderings, where each dimension has a stride value, and row-major or column-major are just two possible resulting interpretations.
[src:numpy-arrays/row-and-column-major-order] Row-major order is the default in NumPy (for Python).
[src:numpy-arrays/row-and-column-major-order] Column-major order is the default in Eigen and Armadillo (both for C++).
[src:numpy-arrays/row-and-column-major-order] A special case would be OpenGL (and OpenGL ES) for graphics processing.
[src:numpy-arrays/row-and-column-major-order] As a result, many developers will now simply declare that having the column as the first index is the definition of column-major, even though this is clearly not the case with a real column-major language like Fortran.
[src:numpy-arrays/row-and-column-major-order] Torch (for Lua) changed from column-major to row-major default order.
[src:numpy-arrays/row-and-column-major-order] As exchanging the indices of an array is the essence of array transposition, an array stored as row-major but read as column-major (or vice versa) will appear transposed.
[src:numpy-arrays/row-and-column-major-order] As actually performing this rearrangement in memory is typically an expensive operation, some systems provide options to specify individual matrices as being stored transposed.
[src:numpy-arrays/row-and-column-major-order] The programmer must then decide whether or not to rearrange the elements in memory, based on the actual usage (including the number of times that the array is reused in a computation).
[src:numpy-arrays/row-and-column-major-order] For example, the Basic Linear Algebra Subprograms functions are passed flags indicating which arrays are transposed.
